<br>
If I remember rightly, it was only two weeks before Luclin was due to be released when Verant bothered us with polls for:<br>
<br>
How much Memory does your machine have?<br>
What Graphics Card does your machine use?<br>
<br>
That was a week *after* Verant announced it's initial minimum specs.<br>
<br>
I think it was extremely poor planning to ask these *vital* research questions at such late notice. It was almost as if somebody at Verant HQ had suddenly realised that not everyone has the level of machine that they were developing on. Shadows of Luclin has cost people a lot more to use than just the price on the box.<br>
<br>
&lt;I&gt;Well testing something this complex even to beta standards would have layered in cost that would have driven SoL to at least $100.&lt;/I&gt;<br>
<br>
Verant has a live test server for this with players that use it and, in effect, get free testing on any upgrade. So why are there so many bugs? It seems to be a case of Verant only fixing things after enough people complain.<br>
<br>
&lt;I&gt;This upgrade is about what I would expect.&lt;/I&gt;<br>
<br>
Really? SoL is the most badly written, resource hungry game I think I've yet come across. The problem is that the new graphics engine still uses the same game engine, the same core code. It's like putting a motorbike engine inside of a jet plane, the only way it's going to get off the ground is if you change various laws of physics.<br>
<br>
A wise man once said: &quot;You can't polish a turd.&quot;.<br>
<br>
But that's what they did, and got away with it for the most part. The only way they could get SoL to run was to get it's users to upgrade their computers to server sized machines. Here's the product you wanted, you're just going to have to move heaven and earth to get it to run.<br>
<br>
It's only due to the lack of competition in the MMORPG market that Everquest still exists. The entire expansion seems little more than a rush job, to keep up with the competition such as DAoC, but without the risk of losing a market that already exists for them. With the future influx of MMORPGs they won't be able to pull the sentimentality trick again though; if Verant have any sense at all they'll rewrite the game engine in it's entireity and transfer everyone over to a completely new system. A fresh coat of paint won't work a second time.<br>
<br>
