<br>
I have about 15 years in the toy, game, and comsumer software industry having worked for Coleco, Milton Bradley, InfoCom, and a few notable consulting companies doing programmer, designer, project manager, producer, etc. I have not done a MMORPG.<br>
<br>
System Requirements -<br>
There is always conflict between the minimum system owned by most potential users and the system needed to produce &quot;an exciting product&quot;. Companies make an error when they produce a product that demands more than the minimum system owned by most potential users.<br>
<br>
Designers are used to designing &quot;inside the  box&quot;. VI's failure to do so is particularly distressing since previous releases had established minimum system requirements and SoL is sold primarily to that user base.<br>
<br>
Testing -<br>
Commercial quality products are routinely tested on 100's of configuration/machines. Perhaps SoL is not intended to be a commercial quality product. Perhaps it's &quot;freeware&quot; and we should be grateful.<br>
<br>
Deployment -<br>
I'm not certain why it was necessary to download data via the patch server for a 3 CD release.<br>
<br>
If the primary purpose for SoL was to attract new customers and returnees, I'm afraid it's not going to have the kind of impact Sony was lead to believe it would. Does it set new standards in appearance, content, and gameplay? Perhaps, but &quot;smooth&quot; and &quot;slick&quot; are not adjectives I'd use to describe this product.<br>
